<p>The <b>Tour de France</b> is an annual <a href="/wiki/Bicycle_racing" title="Bicycle racing">bicycle race</a> that covers more than 3,500&#160;kilometres (2,200&#160;mi) throughout <a href="/wiki/France" title="France">France</a> and a bordering country. The race usually lasts 23 days and attracts cyclists from around the world. The race is broken down into day-long segments, called stages. Individual times to finish each stage are totaled to determine the overall winner for the race. The rider with the least elapsed time each day wears a <a href="/wiki/Yellow_jersey" title="Yellow jersey">yellow jersey</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The course changes every year but it has always finished in <a href="/wiki/Paris" title="Paris">Paris</a>. There are similar races in <a href="/wiki/Giro_d%27Italia" title="Giro d'Italia">Italy</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vuelta_a_Espa%C3%B1a" title="Vuelta a España">Spain</a> but the Tour de France is the oldest, the most prestigious and the best known.</p>
